---
# wandb-driven-dev project config
#
# Copy this file to `.claude/wandb-driven-dev.local.md` in your repo and fill
# in the values. The `edd` skill's first-run interview can also generate this
# for you (`/wandb-driven-dev:edd setup`).

# "entity/project" path on wandb.ai — where every run from this project lands.
wandb_project: ""

launcher:
  # Exact command Claude will copy-paste to launch a training run.
  # Examples:
  #   uv run python scripts/train.py
  #   uv run python k8s/launch.py
  #   sbatch slurm/train.sh
  command: ""

  # How does the launcher get the code onto the compute?
  #   working_tree — runs uncommitted edits as-is from your worktree (local).
  #   clone        — submitter clones origin/HEAD; needs a clean tree + pushed commit.
  #   shared_fs    — compute mounts your working tree (e.g. NFS).
  #   image        — code is baked into a container image, built/pushed before submit.
  reproduction: working_tree

training:
  script: ""        # path to the training entrypoint, e.g. scripts/train.py
  config_dir: ""    # dir containing training configs, e.g. configs/

gpus:
  smoke: 1          # GPU count for short smoke runs (50–200 steps)
  full: 1           # GPU count for full experiments

metrics:
  # Wandb keys driving pass/fail. The first one is treated as the headline
  # metric for sorting result tables.
  decision: []
  # Keys watched for divergence / NaN during smoke and review.
  health: []

curves:
  # W&B's built-in history x-axis. Keep this default unless the project has a
  # better semantic step key for specific metrics.
  default_step_key: _step
  # Exact metric keys and namespace wildcards are supported.
  # Examples:
  #   train/*: train/global_step
  #   val/*: train/global_step
  #   stage_4e/*: stage_4e/epoch
  metric_step_keys: {}
  # Extra keys for setup_project.py discovery to consider.
  candidate_step_keys: [_step]

# Project-level W&B metadata discovered during setup.
# This stores keys and decisions only, never run summaries or metric values.
wandb_metadata: {}
---

# Project notes

This section is free-form. Anything you'd want Claude to know about this
project that doesn't fit the structured schema above. Examples:

- Dataset quirks (e.g. the train split has duplicates that bias accuracy by ~2%).
- Known-good baseline run IDs to pin against.
- Naming conventions you already follow (e.g. tags scheme, group conventions).
- Launcher gotchas (e.g. "always pass `--num_gpus 8` for the full run, the
  config default is 1").
- Things that have burned you before.

The agents read this body verbatim as context, so write in plain prose.
